{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"83b8a0bc-71cf-44a8-993b-ea9d8096c97b","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Look for `.ips` crash logs in:**\n\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user-level)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-level)\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp-2026-05-11-*.ips`.\n\n**You can also use Console.app:**\n1. Open **Console.app**\n2. Navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar\n3. Find your app's report\n\n**For core dumps** (if you want a full memory dump), enable them first:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n```\n\nThen reproduce the crash — the core dump will appear at `/tmp/core.<PID>`.\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash log is usually sufficient for stack traces. If you need to symbolicate .NET runtime frames in it, consider using the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"be3fcbe5-3e21-4b0d-8fe4-fe5468e8c7e9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app that crashed on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files) in specific locations. For NativeAOT apps (which don't use the CoreCLR runtime and thus don't ship `createdump`), you rely on macOS's built-in crash reporting.","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"A0C2:180EFF:90E553:B3487D:6A0136AF"},"id":"f23f2c10-42c0-47d3-bc96-2fc654a10509","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:54:02.667Z","parentId":"52d6d7d6-86f1-4d13-9066-5c5038b5eb76"}
